<p>The strategy is not a substitute for valuation discipline. If an investor is steadily buying a wildly overpriced market, future returns may still disappoint, as Japan after 1989 demonstrated. But for diversified investors contributing over decades, regular buying reduces the temptation to make heroic forecasts and keeps the plan tied to income rather than headlines.</p>
